<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=9692&amp;p=106005#p106005</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=9692&amp;p=106005#p106005"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: NES Sprite Animator]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=9692&amp;p=106005#p106005"><![CDATA[
To get a 1 pixel brush in Gimp 2.8, I click pencil, then I click on the brush shape (big square in the &quot;tool options&quot; pane), for me the second brush was a little dot, it's called &quot;1. Pixel&quot;. Finally there is a &quot;size&quot; field just below, change that to 1.00, and you should be able to draw hard pixels.<br /><br />I also recomend going to preferences &gt; tool options, and telling it to save the tool options on exit so you don't have to do this every time.<br /><br />For other tools like the eraser, some of them have individual options for anti-aliasing or hard edges. Eraser has a &quot;hard edge&quot; option you want to turn on, for example.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=5165">rainwarrior</a> — Fri Jan 11, 2013 11:44 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
